<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-13T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-13T02:00:00-05:00" n="629" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d629">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">394.115 Panay/24: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-13T15:00:00+08:00">December 13, 1937—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 13—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1142. Japanese Consulate General informs us by telephone that large
                            seaplane will leave early tomorrow morning and land on river <pb facs="0500" n="492" xml:id="pg_492"/> in vicinity of Hohsien. Plane
                            is to carry doctors, nurses and medical supplies.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Hankow, repeated to Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>